segments.text: I just want to mention something I want to make sure I covered.
Please do.
Over the, you know, the constant thing over the 30 or so years has been teaching that one course and being a graduate advisor in the department.
So a lot of interaction with undergraduate and graduate students, which I've enjoyed in both cases.
And I've been offered, I mean, I've been asked so many times,
How in the world do you keep teaching that same course for 30 years?
Well, that I don't know.
Don't really have an answer for that, except it's different students here a semester.
This is my last semester to do it this time, and I'm just as decided about it as I'd ever be.
Kind of feels funny.
I just can't imagine not continuing to do it, to tell you the truth.
But I've continued to enjoy it.
But I've always tried to,
at least every couple of semesters, do something different about the course.
Add something about redoing audio tapes, or now I put all the objectives on the web.
Last semester I did that.
So something to keep me a little bit current, and something also to use different visual aids,
And never to be too rigid in the lecture.
I always kind of let it flow and cover things in different order.
But in addition to that, I think in the university community, there's so many opportunities to, I guess, be a servant or grow yourself.
And so over the years, I've advised student clubs.
Sometimes many as four at one time, but mainly I've always had at least one.
advised corps outfits, served as advisor to the political forum, a student group shortly after he came here.
Got to meet Gerald Ford and a few other prominent people in those years and enjoyed the heck out of that.
Then served a couple of years on the MSC consul and directory.
That's a different...
Faculty Senate had no intent.
People said, and the department said, we need, you know, we need to have somebody from the department be on the Faculty Senate.
So I get, I mean, I didn't say anything to anybody.
I get nominated, and I end up on the Faculty Senate, and then...
Oh, Fred Smines over in Rain Science said, well, it's a shame.
We're just going to let John McNairman be the first speaker with no competition at all.
Somebody ought to run against him.
Milford, you run against him.
Well, I did.
Well, of course, and fortunate, deservedly, John, he's elected.
But John makes me the deputy and then...
Of course this greases a pill for me to be the speaker the next year.
But I'm keeping all my teaching duties and all my advice all at the same time.
But that was a, see that was an outlet of different, and of course the speaker year was a,
I was a tremendous experience to interact with all of the higher administrators and that kind of deal.
And it was an exciting time for the Senate trying to get established.
Did the Senate come up with any recommendation that you thought was a little goofy that you still had as their voice to support?
No, I don't remember.
And this happened actually after my year of speaker was over.
the core curriculum was being developed during that year, all that year.
And I'm not particularly proud of it, but I ended up in the final analysis voting against the final adoption of the core curriculum.
Not because I opposed the core curriculum, but because there was always in the development of it, there'd been, I quote, a technological requirement anticipated in it.
And this got washed out
at the end, and I felt so strongly about that that I ended up voting no, and I didn't feel real good about that, but I didn't have to promote that to the Senate.
No, I don't remember anything.
I'm trying to remember it had something to do with women's program or something.
Gosh, I don't know if I have any notes about this or not, but Dr. Vandenberg called me into his office, and he was mad as a hornet.
I mean, he was off the wall for just two or three minutes.
Then he calmed down, and we had a good conversation, but I, it was something about the women's program.
I think something that Ms.
Shaffer, Dr. Shaffer was,
Was the woman in charge of the women's committee program?
I don't remember the particulars, but I do remember Dr. Vanderbilt.
He was mightily upset when he first went in, but he calmed down.
He calmed down.
What do you think?
But I did that, and then I became a continuous improvement facilitator.
Let's stay with faculty senate just a second.
What do you think the faculty's role
in decision making for this institution ought to be?
You know, I'm kind of comfortable with the Senate being in an advisory role.

I'm not one of those that, quote, thinks the faculty needs to make all the decisions, because the faculty is just one component in the whole university community, and the university president ultimately, yeah, an organized venue by which the faculty can make its...
to make its feelings known.
And I think on matters of academics, it's, I would hope, I would hope that the president, and I think all of them have tended to support Senate decisions.
There have been exceptions, I guess, but.
In the department, should there be a department head or a department chairman?
Hmm.
Well, for an apartment like ours with a three agency deal and responsibilities out state and in state, I think it needs to be ahead.

through wednesday whether or not they qualified or not well i think it i don't know but i remember it worked back three or four days oh so it got earlier in there kept getting earlier and earlier you had to turn in senior grades and it came farce because seniors were just i mean i taught a bit classic would have a
25% seniors, and I guess I did begin to get a little chapped about not taking finals because they would put off classes like mine for the last semester, so they didn't have to take my final.
Of all of those services, which ones were the most satisfying to you as you look back?
Each one while I was doing it.
I wouldn't want to pick one.
I guess the most different, of course, was being speaker of the faculty senate for you.
Maybe that was the headiest kind of thing, you know.
Get you tickets to the Texas game and all.
A few things like that I remember very well.
But no, in the early days, being an advisor to a corps outfit, having come through the corps,
There were a lot of good experiences associated with that.
How do you feel about the Corps as you look back on it now?
What do you feel about the Corps today?
Much more military than it was then.
Is it better, worse, plus, minus?
Haven't had real close contact in recent years, enough to see much on the inside.
I think it's been, yeah, many more people, I guess you could say, many more people in the Corps who really have a kind of a pro-military posture.
See, when I came through the Corps, many of us were there because we had to be there.
It was either be in the Corps or be in Korea.
The Corps was preferable.

So you had a major, major influence in the Corps of people who were, yeah, we could kind of tolerate the bull and that kind of stuff and enjoy some of it, but we never had any dream about being a military somebody.
I feel like there's been more
And I think a lot of that's been, maybe gotten rid of in recent years, but I feel like there's been a lot more, what I would just call, really cheap stuff to go on.
During all those years, describe a typical week for you during the academic year.
You started at Monday and did what, and how long, and so forth.
Take through a week.
How many nights were you busy and so forth?
Well, with all of the kind of extracurricular activities and things I've had, there's probably not very many nights when I didn't have a meeting or do something at home related to a job.
I've normally, I've been a bicycle rider for a long time.
I've normally, and I like to get here on a bicycle before the traffic gets too bad and I've normally not gone home until it's not too bad again.
So,
I've typically been at work from 7.30, 7.45 in the morning until 5.30 or 6 in the afternoon and usually bring lunch.
We have a bridge playing group here, lunch.
But during the school year, most of the time, I had an 8 o'clock class on Monday, Wednesday, Friday.
and so you have to get here early to be ready to go for that, and I've had 11.30 for many years now, 11.30 to 12.20 class, so even for the Brady playing group, that cuts you lots of hours a little.
And what was this second class?
The same class.
Oh, same, two sections.
Two sections, okay.
Two sections, same class.
And what did you tell your students that your office hours were for them to come by?
Never had office hours.
The door was open.
I always told them the door was open.
call me, now it's email.
You're welcome to come in any time you can catch me.
That's what I always said.
But I've never set rigid off the hours.
How would you compare the quality of the students now with the students when you first got here?
That's a hard read.
I suspect the overall quality in terms of academic capability is better.
in terms of maturity in the sense of the student knowing who they are and what they're about is not as good now as it was.
Class attendance generally is much poorer than it was in those days.
Students can't take nearly as heavy a load as I do it.
They have, I don't know how many of them spend their time, but I mean I can visualize some of the options.
when you see them unload all the things they have.
I mean, there's TV, there's the internet, there's music, all of them have cars, they're mobile, they leave here on weekends.
I just think there are a lot of competing things for students' attention.
I don't see as much interest in learning.
As a general rule, I just don't see as much interest in learning.
I just didn't get a degree, but I don't see much interest in learning.
In that course that you've been doing all these years, do you think you, how does your grading system now, in other words, what does it take to make an A now compared to then?
I'd like to tell you it hasn't changed much.
But not nearly as many make A's now.
Is that right?
No, sir.
What about flunking?

many more today many more many more yeah one to three percent in the early days it runs uh in the seven six to ten now i always thought i had to have at least fifteen percent a's in class i mean i felt bad if i didn't have at least fifteen percent a's and lots of semesters i'd have over fifty percent a's and b's
About 35% of A's and B's now, most of the time.
It varies from semester to semester.
Last summer, not this past summer, but summer before, had a real good class, but this past summer, terrible.
Now, this fall, looks like, I mean, I had 142, I had 162 in class Monday.
Well, that's not bad.
What about women enrollment in the class now compared to years ago?
I've had some summer classes with more women than men.
This semester seems that my percentage of women is quite a bit lower than it's been some time.
And I'm assuming far more urban kids now.
Oh yeah, for sure, for sure.
Many internationals in the undergraduate course?
Not many, not many, probably 5% less.
I bet there are a lot more from broken homes than there would have been 20 years ago.
I think that's the big change.
I think kids are about as honest as there have been.
I think the ability's there.
I think the maturity factor in terms of them feeling good about themselves, having a well-developed
Ethel's code to live by.
I just think many of them are not there.
Do you have much indication of scholastic dishonesty now?
No, I wouldn't say.
That's what I say.
I think they're about as honest as there have been.
I don't see.
I've had a little of that all along, but I don't think they're any less honest.
I think I've always said students tend to live up or down to your expectations in that arena.
You have high expectations of them in terms of honesty.
I think you generally get it.
How many students do you reckon you taught in that class?
I have a record downstairs.
I don't think I made 18,000, but I'm close.
Between 17,500 and 18,000.
All right, now I'm getting near the end.
Among your departmental colleagues, to whom do you feel the greatest appreciation?
I'm not gonna ask you the negative.
Which colleagues are you more grateful to?
Well, probably Larry Wilding in terms of what a colleague has meant to me personally in my own professional life.
I think a lot of people in the department would probably say that.
Larry's made us all better.
He's certainly been a strong plus for me in some of the things I've been able to experience and do.
Hank Mills was a
Somebody I always have a lot of respect for.
He was a very different guy.
Only had a master's degree.
Old East Texas country boy.
But I guess in the early years I had about as close association with him as anybody.
Some pretty good country wisdom there that he could impart.
He could read students.
You're inferring he was a buddy?
Yeah, kind of, yeah.
Who's been your closest buddies, friends, in the department or elsewhere on the campus?
You know, I don't think I could say that I've been, I don't think I've,
single on anybody like that.
We have a departmental bridge group, gets together once a month, and so I guess you, Larry, Larry and Gladys.
So Larry and Gladys are probably, by virtue of church and department and everything, they've probably been closer to them.
They were quite close to the Runge's during their years here.
Marcia was always close to Doris Darby.

And the Sigrid Van Butten lives down the street, but I was never, you know, always liked to interact with Ron and Hans, but never, I've never, I guess you'd have to say Larry, and yet we don't spend a lot of time together.
All right, looking up in the hierarchy,
to whom do you think, because of what they have meant to the institution, do you feel the greatest gratitude at the college and at the institution level?
Who did the most to make A&M better, you think, at the college?
Well, of course, I don't have that whole perception.
At the university, I'd have to say,
Okay.
And it doesn't have to be just one, are they?
He was the man in the spot at the time.
I mean, obviously his service here preceded me, but I think he probably considered where A&M was when it came or where it was going when he left.
He probably had the most profound influence on anybody that I could think of.
In the college?
Mm-hmm.
I'm guessing that Patterson probably did as much to wake it up to what it could possibly be, and that's more hearsay than any knowledge.
I've never done any very big study on that.
Probably Harry Conkle.
He had strengths and weaknesses, but I think
I think I'd have to say here.
The department has to be Bloodworth without a shadow of a doubt.
Let's make believe that you've been recruited now as the consultant to advise the department and the college and the institution of what it should do in the future.
What would you advise this department to do in the future?
I'm going to go at it the backward way a little bit.
Institution.
I hope we don't lose sight of what it is that I think makes A&M unique in terms of can-do attitude, friendliness, openness, that kind of thing.
And I think some of those things that contribute most to making it what
I've always said in my classes, you know, I've been to Wisconsin, I've been to Cornell, I've been here.
I'm not about to tell you that Texas A&M's the best institution I've ever been associated with, but I am going to tell you it's unique.
And I really believe it's unique.
And particularly what I consider the positive parts of that uniqueness I hope we don't lose.
And I don't think those points are gonna help us be top 10.
I mean, I think if you get all wrapped up in being top 10, we can lose.
We can lose some things that may not contribute to us being top 10, but make us unique in a desirable way.
So I hope as an institution we don't lose sight of that.
In a department, there obviously,

there needs to be an ability to to bring all areas along in it well we're going to have to identify it probably to an extent we haven't done we're going to have to identify the areas where we want to be top flight and where we just want to be meet our
quote, academic responsibilities, I don't think we can be, I don't think we can be everything to everybody.
And I think, at the college level, I think Ed Heiler has a, you know, that's one of the things I kind of fault him on.
I think he's not gotten beyond us thinking we can be everything to everybody.
So we've not made some hard decisions there that we probably could make.
And we probably haven't made some hard ones in the department that we need to make.
the balance that right now in terms of grant dollars, the biotech, genetics, molecular biology, they're swinging the big stick.

I think there's a threat to the whole land-grant system stemming out of this with the increased emphasis on patenting genes, on getting royalties that goes back into plant breeders and geneticists' pockets.
that an increasing percentage of the support to do the research is coming from soft money sources.
There's not, there tends to be not nearly in new faculty the sense of servanthood that I think befits people in colleges of agriculture and land grant institutions.
We're losing some of that.

And it's causing, and maybe that's the biggest challenge I see in the department, is to maintain that spirit of serving the taxpayers who make it possible for you to be here and not have such a high emphasis on feathering your own nest.
I tend to become more materialistic as a faculty.
I don't like that.
Are there some specialties within this department's scope that you think ought to get emphasis?
You said can't be all things to all people.
Well, for the major commodities in the state, grain circle of corn, cotton, wheat, small grains,
we need to maintain a continuity of expertise from the very base level to the top.
Because in many cases, the market for the products is not sufficiently large.
It's gonna attract the large seed companies, and they're getting bigger all the time.
So they only wanna do things that are
where there's a big market for a product.
So we have to meet the niche for those commodities.
We have to maintain expertise in soil science as it relates to land use in the broadest sense from waste disposal to conservation to

agricultural production to sustainability, more and more we're going to see the emphasis be more, at least short term, it's going to be more environmentally oriented, more urban concern oriented than it is, has been a traditional field crop agriculture.
But here's some bias from cropping.
But I think we'd be terribly remiss if we let our expertise and the broad range of
of soil science, Paul.
But we need to, we can't, we can't be really expert in all those areas.
And I'd say we'd probably sacrifice some of what have been a traditional basic science, like soil physics.
We have to have people that are functioning more at the interface maybe between, let's say, soils and environmental concerns, soils ecology, environmental
There'll be more emphasis on integrating that.
And hopefully a lot more cooperation between departments.
You know, the department wall is a terrible barrier.
Now we have the faculty.
The faculties are across departments.
I don't know, there's no easy answer to that kind of thing.

If we could smooth out the barriers that prevent faculty from interacting across departmental walls, and faculty walls, and college walls, seem to be functioning better between universities than we can between right here on our own campus, in some instances.
That's a big deal with Douglas,
interacting more, but I wanted to do it and doing it, two different things.
What were your proudest moments in all these years as a faculty member here?
I guess maybe getting a note from a student that's in whose life, the note seems to say that you had a very positive impact on it.
Because I know how many people think they're going to have a note like that and never do.
How many times I've thought about doing something like that to be good.
So, I think that would be my proudest moment, is to get those favorable comments.
And there's not a whole lot of them, but when you do get them,
questions.
Summarize what you have in your heart about what it's meant to you to be a faculty member here.
Okay.
Well, I feel just extremely fortunate and blessed.
I mean, I couldn't have done what I love to do and got paid for it.
Family's had a good living.
It's been, I've felt that I've had wonderful support, a lot of opportunities to interact with literally
thousands, thousands of students at both graduate and undergraduate level
